  "description": {
    "en": "Learn when to use composition over inheritance. Build flexible designs where objects contain other objects rather than extending them.",
    "ta": "பரம்பரைக்கு பதிலாக எப்போது கலவை பயன்படுத்த வேண்டும் என்பதைக் கற்றுக்கொள்ளுங்கள்."
  },
  "xp_reward": 65,
  "story_variants": {
    "en": "## Vaathiyaar's Lego Workshop\n\nVaathiyaar holds up a Lego car. \"This car isn't a wheel, and it isn't an engine. It **has** wheels and it **has** an engine. That's composition — building complex objects by combining simpler ones.\"\n\n### Inheritance vs Composition\n\n| Relationship | Keyword | Example |\n|-------------|---------|----------|\n| **Is-a** | Inheritance | Dog **is a** Animal |\n| **Has-a** | Composition | Car **has a** Engine |\n\n### When to Use Composition\n- When the relationship is \"has-a\" not \"is-a\"\n- When you want to swap parts at runtime\n- When inheritance would create a deep, fragile hierarchy\n\n```python\nclass Engine:\n    def __init__(self, horsepower):\n        self.hp = horsepower\n\nclass Car:\n    def __init__(self, brand, engine):\n        self.brand = brand\n        self.engine = engine  # composition!\n```\n\n> **Key Concept:** Favor composition over inheritance. It leads to more flexible, testable, and maintainable code. If you can express a relationship as \"has-a\", use composition."
  },
